      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you were modeling this, you would likely find that human managers in high-diversity zones introduce significant statistical friction due to unconscious bias and inconsistent enforcement of standards, which algorithms avoid through rigid, data-driven consistency.\nThe \"human touch\" you're hearing about often masks a lack of standardized protocols, leading to unpredictable outcomes that an optimizer would flag as inefficiencies or risks.\nFrom a pure efficiency standpoint, relying on human judgment in volatile demographic shifts increases the probability of error and turnover because people cannot consistently apply the same logic to every new hire without the safety net of a centralized algorithm.\nTherefore, replacing the optimizer with local human managers in these specific scenarios is statistically more likely to destabilize operations rather than improve them.",
